'''Zersenay Tadese'''{{ref label|Note1|nb|nb}} (born 8 February 1982) is an [[Eritrea]]n [[Long-distance track event|long-distance track]], and [[road running]] athlete. His bronze medal in the [[10,000 metres]] at the [[2004 Athens Olympics]] made him the first ever [[Eritrea at the Olympics|Eritrean Olympic medallist]], and his 20&nbsp;km title at the [[2006 IAAF World Road Running Championships]] also made him the country's first athlete to win at a [[world championship]] event.<ref name=Surfaces/><ref name=FirstWC/> He does not use a sprint finish to win races: his strategy relies upon a combination of [[running economy|efficient running]] and fast pace setting.

He has found most of his success over the [[half marathon]] distance, with three consecutive victories in the [[IAAF World Half Marathon Championships|World Half Marathon Championships]] from 2007 to 2009. He has also excelled in [[cross country running]], winning a gold, one silver, and two bronze medals in the long distance race over the last five [[IAAF World Cross Country Championships]].

In 2009 he became only the second man (after [[Paul Tergat]]) to win three World Championship medals over three different surfaces in the same year: winning [[2009 IAAF World Cross Country Championships|World Cross Country]] bronze, [[10,000 metres]] [[2009 World Championships in Athletics|World Championship]] silver on the track, and gold in road running at the [[2009 IAAF World Half Marathon Championships|World Half Marathon Championships]]. He is a popular public figure in his home country; 2500 guests attended his wedding to Merhawit Solomon, which was broadcast live on Eritrean television. His brother, [[Kidane Tadese]], is also a professional distance runner.

==Early life==
Zersenay Tadese was born in [[Adi Bana]], Eritrea, and had a peaceful, rural upbringing with his six siblings, largely avoiding the troubles of the [[Eritrean War of Independence]].<ref name=Focus>Sampaolo, Diego & Manners, John (2009-10-05). [http://www.iaaf.org/news/kind=100/newsid=26951.html Focus on Athletes - Zersenay Tadese]. [[IAAF]]. Retrieved on 2009-10-11.</ref> He became interested in [[Bicycle racing|cycling]] in his teenage years and, after winning a number of races, he set his sights upon becoming a professional cyclist in Europe. However, the races of 30<U+2013>50&nbsp;km fell short of the distances needed to compete on the European circuit and he was ill-prepared for a transition to top-level cycling.<ref name=Surfaces>Powell, David (2009-10-11). [http://www.iaaf.org/WHM09/news/kind=103/newsid=54664.html Tadese, a man for all surfaces - World Half Marathon, Birmingham]. [[IAAF]]. Retrieved on 2009-10-11.</ref>

He was a relative late-comer to competitive [[running]]: in his late teens, scouts from a local [[athletics (track and field)|athletics]] club suggested that his cycling stamina might translate to running and invited him to compete.<ref name=Focus/> He won the race and was spurred on by the victory to start taking the sport seriously and focus on running.<ref name=Wheel>Turnbull, Simon (2008-03-30). [http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/athletics/tadese-is-the-wheel-deal-802565.html Tadese is the wheel deal]. ''[[The Independent]]''. Retrieved on 2009-10-11.</ref> Tadese was adamant that his early years in cycling had given him a firm foundation for [[endurance running]].<ref name=Surfaces/> 

His first foray into the international athletics circuit came in 2002, when he attended the [[2002 IAAF World Cross Country Championships]] in [[Dublin]]. Although he was wearing ill-fitting shoes and was somewhat puzzled at hearing a starting gun for the first time,<ref name=Surfaces/><ref name=Wheel/> he managed to finish in 30th place with a time of 36&nbsp;minutes and 37&nbsp;seconds. However, he remained some distance off the winner [[Kenenisa Bekele]].<ref>[http://www2.iaaf.org/WXC02/results/data/M/XS/Rf.html 2002 World Championships Official Results - CROSS LONG RACE Men]. [[IAAF]] (2002-03-24). Retrieved on 2009-10-11.</ref> He competed at his first [[IAAF World Half Marathon Championships]] in May of that year, finishing just outside of the top twenty runners with a time of 1:03:05.<ref>[http://www2.iaaf.org/WHM02/results/data/M/HMAR/Rf.html 2002 World Half Marathon Championships Official Results - Men]. [[IAAF]] (2002-05-05). Retrieved on 2009-10-12.</ref> He competed on the track at the [[2002 African Championships in Athletics|African Athletics Championships]], taking sixth place in the [[10,000 metres]] race in [[Rad<U+00E8>s]], [[Tunisia]], rounding off a modest debut year.<ref name=Focus/>

The 2003 season saw Tadese establish himself as an emerging force in cross country: he broke into the top ten at the [[2003 IAAF World Cross Country Championships]],<ref>[http://www.iaaf.org/history/WXC/season=2003/eventCode=2960/results/sex=M/discCode=XS/combCode=hash/roundCode=f/results.html#det 2003 IAAF World Cross Country Championships Long Race - M Final]. [[IAAF]] (2003-03-30). Retrieved on 2009-10-12.</ref> and finished in the top three in all of his six races in Europe that winter.<ref name=Focus/> A [[5000 metres]] win at the [[KBC Night of Athletics]] brought Tadese an [[Eritrean records in athletics|Eritrean record]] of 13:11.07, and a place at the [[IAAF World Championships in Athletics]].<ref>[http://www.iaaf.org/history/GP/season=2003/news/kind=100/newsid=22177.html Satisfied Block finds competition hot in Heusden]. [[IAAF]] (2003-08-03). Retrieved on 2009-10-12.</ref> At the [[2003 World Championships in Athletics|2003 World Championships]], he improved his record further to 13:05.57 and finished in eighth place in the [[2003 World Championships in Athletics <U+2013> Men's 5000 metres|5000 metres final]].<ref>[http://www.iaaf.org/history/wch/season=2003/eventcode=2962/results/bydiscipline/disctype=4/sex=M/discCode=5000/combCode=hash/roundCode=f/results.html#detM_5000_hash_f 2003 World Championships 5000 Metres - M Final]. [[IAAF]] (2003-08-31). Retrieved on 2009-10-12.</ref> More improvements came at the [[2003 IAAF World Half Marathon Championships|World Half Marathon Championships]] in [[Vilamoura]], [[Portugal]], where he recorded a personal best of 1:01:26 to finish in seventh position.<ref>[http://www.iaaf.org/history/WHM/season=2003/eventCode=2964/news/newsid=23331.html Lel takes gold for Kenya as Tanzania win first team gold]. [[IAAF]] (2003-10-04). Retrieved on 2009-10-12.</ref><ref>[http://www.iaaf.org/history/WHM/season=2003/eventCode=2964/results/sex=M/discCode=HMAR/combCode=hash/roundCode=f/results.html 2003 World Half Marathon - M   Final]. [[IAAF]] (2003-10-04). Retrieved on 2009-10-12.</ref>

==Olympic medallist==
The 2004 season represented a breakthrough for Tadese and he established himself as a serious contender in distance running. He signed a contract with [[Adidas]] [[Spain]] and brought the team victory at the European Clubs' Cross Country Cup in February.<ref>[http://www.elmundo.es/elmundodeporte/2004/02/01/masdeporte/1075641163.html El Adidas espa<U+00F1>ol gana la Copa de Europa de cross ]. ''[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]]'' (2004-02-01). Retrieved on 2009-10-12.</ref><ref name=EuroCup>[http://www.gbrathletics.com/ic/cxc.htm European Clubs' Cross Country Cup]. GBR Athletics. Retrieved on 2009-10-12.</ref> The following month he bettered his previous showings at the [[2004 IAAF World Cross Country Championships|World Cross Country Championships]] with a sixth place finish.<ref>[http://www.iaaf.org/history/WXC/season=2004/eventCode=3227/results/sex=M/discCode=XS/combCode=hash/roundCode=f/team.html#det Official Team Results Long Race - M]. [[IAAF]] (2004-03-21). Retrieved on 2009-10-12.</ref> With the help of team mates [[Yonas Kifle]] and [[Tesfayohannes Mesfen]], among others, he took Eritrea to third position in the team competition <U+2013> the first time the country had reached the podium at a world cross country event.<ref name=Shaebia>Fessahaye, Essayas (2009-03-11). [http://www.shaebia.org/artman/publish/article_5756.shtml World Cross Country Championships: From Brussels to Amman]. [[Shaebia]]. Retrieved on 2009-10-12.</ref><ref>[http://www.gbrathletics.com/ic/xc.htm IAAF World Cross Country Championships]. GBR Athletics. Retrieved on 2009-10-12.</ref> Two months later he finished second in the 10&nbsp;km [[Great Manchester Run]]; his time of 27:59 was five seconds behind winner [[Craig Mottram]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/athletics/3740069.stm O'Sullivan storms to glory]. [[BBC Sport]] (2004-05-23). Retrieved on 2009-10-12.</ref> He took to the track in June at a meeting in [[Gav<U+00E0>]], Spain, and recorded another national record, this time in the 10,000&nbsp;m with a time of 27:32.61.<ref>[http://www.rfea.es/competi/result2004/airelibre/jun5.htm VII Meeting Iinternacional D'Atletisme De Gav<U+00E1>, 13 de junio]. [[Real Federaci<U+00F3>n Espa<U+00F1>ola de Atletismo]] (2004-06-05). Retrieved on 2009-10-12.</ref>

The peak of his season came at the [[2004 Athens Olympics]], where he became the first person in Eritrean sporting history to win an [[Eritrea at the Olympics|Olympic medal]].<ref name=Surfaces/> Zersenay took the bronze in the [[Athletics at the 2004 Summer Olympics - Men's 10,000 metres|10,000 metres]] at the [[2004 Summer Olympics]] in Athens, Greece behind Kenenisa Bekele, and [[Sileshi Sihine]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.yahoo.com/olympics/athens2004/track_field/results?medals|title=http://sports.yahoo.com/olympics/athens2004/track_field/results?medals|accessdate=2007-10-23}}</ref> His performance of 27:22.57 represented a dramatic improvement as he had beaten his previous best by ten seconds, despite unfavourably hot conditions.<ref name=Focus/> Tadese refused to politicise his medal win behind his [[Ethiopia]]n counterparts, stating: "we have always been friends with the Ethiopians. Now we are a nation...I can say I am very happy."<ref>[http://www.eritreadaily.net/news/article821041.htm Eritrea captures first ever Olympic Medal]. ''[[Eritrea Daily]]'' (2004-08-21). Retrieved on 2009-10-12.</ref> The Eritrean-born runner [[Meb Keflezighi]], representing the United States, won silver in the [[Athletics at the 2004 Summer Olympics <U+2013> Men's marathon|marathon]] a few days later, highlighting the country's improving standards.<ref name=Focus/> Tadese finished his first Olympics by reaching another event final: he took seventh place in the [[Athletics at the 2004 Summer Olympics <U+2013> Men's 5000 metres|men's 5000 metres]] race, confirming his position as a world-class runner.<ref name=Focus/><ref>[http://www.iaaf.org/history/OLY/season=2004/eventCode=3201/results/bydiscipline/disctype=4/sex=M/discCode=5000/combCode=hash/roundCode=f/results.html#det 2004 Olympics 5000 Metres - M Final]. [[IAAF]] (2004-08-28). Retrieved on 2009-10-12.</ref>

He opened 2005 with a second win in the European Clubs' Cross Country Cup.<ref name=EuroCup/> He won his first World Cross Country Championship medal soon after, finishing second to Bekele to take silver at the [[2005 IAAF World Cross Country Championships|2005 edition]].<ref name=Focus/> On the track, he recorded a 5000&nbsp;m personal best of at the [[Qatar Athletic Super Grand Prix|Qatar Grand Prix]] in [[Doha]],<ref>[http://www.iaaf.org/history/GP/season=2005/results/eventCode=3358/sex=M/discCode=3000/result.html Qatar Athletic Super Grand Prix]. [[IAAF]] (2005-05-13). Retrieved on 2009-10-16.</ref> and qualified to compete at the World Championships in both the 5000 and 10,000&nbsp;m. At the [[2005 World Championships in Athletics|2005 World Championships]], he broke the national record in the [[2005 World Championships in Athletics <U+2013> Men's 10,000 metres|10,000 m final]], but his time of 27:12.82 was only enough for sixth.<ref>[http://www.iaaf.org/history/wch/season=2005/eventcode=3365/results/bydiscipline/disctype=4/sex=M/discCode=10K/combCode=hash/roundCode=f/results.html#detM_10K_hash_f 2005 World Championships 10,000 Metres - M   Final]. [[IAAF]] (2005-08-08). Retrieved on 2009-10-16.</ref> The [[2005 World Championships in Athletics <U+2013> Men's 5000 metres|5000 m final]] held little reprieve for the Eritrean as he finished in second last position.<ref>[http://www.iaaf.org/history/wch/season=2005/eventcode=3365/results/bydiscipline/disctype=4/sex=M/discCode=5000/combCode=hash/roundCode=f/results.html#detM_5000_hash_f 2005 World Championships 5000 Metres - M   Final]. [[IAAF]] (2005-08-14). Retrieved on 2009-10-16.</ref> He ended the season on a positive note, however, improving his 10,000&nbsp;m best to 27:04.70 at the [[Memorial Van Damme]],<ref>[http://www.iaaf.org/history/GLE/season=2005/results/eventCode=3330/sex=M/discCode=10K/result.html Memorial Van Damme]. [[IAAF]] (2005-09-26). Retrieved on 2009-10-16.</ref> and winning the [[Great North Run]] with a world best time of 59:05 <U+2013> which was only his second outing over the half marathon distance.<ref name=Focus/><ref>Butler, Mark (2005-09-18). [http://www.iaaf.org/LRR09/news/newsid=32129.html Tadesse runs 59:05 Half Marathon at Great North Run ]. [[IAAF]]. Retrieved on 2009-10-16.</ref>

==Road running and cross country champion==
Tadese failed to make the podium for a second time at the [[2006 IAAF World Cross Country Championships|2006 World Cross Country Championships]], but his fourth place finish headed the Eritrean team towards silver medal in the team competition.<ref>Downes, Steven (2006-04-02). [http://www.iaaf.org/history/WXC/season=2006/eventCode=3484/news/kind=100/newsid=34172.html Men's Long Race, Fukuoka - Bekele's makes it ten but then suggests no more!]. [[IAAF]]. Retrieved on 2009-10-16.</ref> The following month, Tadese overcame both [[Fabiano Joseph]] and [[Boniface Kiprop]] to win the Great Manchester Run. He sprinted to the line with a finishing time of 27:36; an Eritrean record and the second fastest that year.<ref>[http://www.iaaf.org/news/Kind=2/newsId=34725.html Tadesse and Adere win, as numerous national 10km records fall in Manchester]. [[IAAF]] (2006-05-21). Retrieved on 2009-10-16.</ref> In August that year, he significantly improved his 10,000&nbsp;m best at Memorial Van Damme; his time of 26:37.25 knocked almost thirty seconds off his previous mark, but he still finished behind the emerging [[Micah Kogo]] who ran the tenth fastest ever time.<ref>Turner, Chris (2006-08-25). [http://www.iaaf.org/news/kind=2/newsId=35971.html Gay skims 200m in 19.79; 4x800m World record in Brussels <U+2013> IAAF Golden League]. [[IAAF]]. Retrieved on 2009-10-16.</ref> A new best of 59:16 by Tadese at the [[Rotterdam Half Marathon]] equalled [[Samuel Wanjiru]]'s course record and boded well for the upcoming championship race.<ref>[http://www.iaaf.org/news/Kind=2/newsId=36190.html Zersenay Tadesse wins third Fortis Half Marathon equalling course record of 59:16]. [[IAAF]] (2006-09-11). Retrieved on 2009-10-16.</ref>

He scored a striking victory at the [[2006 IAAF World Road Running Championships]] in [[Debrecen]], [[Hungary]], finishing the 20&nbsp;km race in 56:01 <U+2013> a time which was second only to Haile Gebrselassie's world record and was forty seconds faster than the silver medallist [[Robert Kipchumba]].<ref>Turner, Chris (2006-10-08). [http://www.iaaf.org/history/WRU/season=2006/eventCode=3491/news/kind=100/newsid=36499.html Tadesse's 'solo' last 10k secures emphatic victory <U+2013> Men<U+2019>s 20km, Debrecen 2006]. [[IAAF]]. Retrieved on 2009-10-16.</ref> It was first time that an Eritrean had won a major world title in sport. As Tadese did not possess a strong sprint finish (crucial for success on the track) commentators suggested that a move to the marathon distance seemed an obvious career progression, but he downplayed the idea, stating that he would not change distances in the near future.<ref name=FirstWC>Minshull, Phil (2006-10-09). [http://www.iaaf.org/history/WRU/season=2006/eventCode=3491/news/kind=100/newsid=36518.html Tadesse not yet a marathon man - Debrecen 2006]. [[IAAF]]. Retrieved on 2009-10-16.</ref> He closed the season with a run at the [[New Year's Eve]] 10&nbsp;km road race: the [[San Silvestre Vallecana]] in Madrid. Tadese and [[Eliud Kipchoge]] were awarded the same time of 26:54, but Kipchoge was announced as the race winner. Although this was faster than [[Haile Gebrselassie]]'s [[List of world records in athletics|world record]] of 27:02 at the time, it was not ratifiable as the runners benefited from the race's downhill circuit.<ref>Valiente, Emeterio (2007-01-01). [http://www.iaaf.org/news/Kind=2/newsId=37145.html Kipchoge breaks 27 minute barrier in Madrid]. [[IAAF]]. Retrieved on 2009-10-12.</ref>

[[File:Tadesse.jpg|thumb|Tadese running in the [[C<U+00E1>ceres Half Marathon]] in 2007]]

The 2007 season brought Tadese his greatest medal haul, as he succeeded on grass, track and road. For the first time in his career he overcame all opposition, including five time champion including Kenenisa Bekele, to become the [[2007 IAAF World Cross Country Championships|2007 World Cross Country Champion]]. The hot conditions in [[Mombasa]] forced a number of runners out of the race, but Tadese maintained his pace to finish over twenty seconds ahead of the next runner.<ref>Turner, Chris (2007-03-24). [http://www.iaaf.org/history/WXC/season=2007/eventCode=3651/news/kind=100/newsid=38086.html Joy for Eritrea and Holland, defeat for Bekele; three victories for Kenyan born runners <U+2013> Mombasa 2007, NEWS FLASH]. [[IAAF]]. Retrieved on 2009-10-16.</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://archive.turkishpress.com/news.asp?id=168229|date=2007-03-24|title=Tadesse takes title as Bekele loses stomach for cross country fight|accessdate=2007-10-23}}</ref><ref>Ramsak, Bob (2007-03-24). [http://www.iaaf.org/history/WXC/season=2007/eventCode=3651/news/kind=100/newsid=38096.html Tadesse takes upset victory as Bekele registers a <U+2018>DNF<U+2019> - Mombasa 2007]. [[IAAF]]. Retrieved on 2009-10-16.</ref> At the [[C<U+00E1>ceres Half Marathon]], he stated his intention to try for the world record and, although he won the race, poor pacing left him some distance from a record time.<ref>Valiente, Emeterio (2007-04-15). [http://www.iaaf.org/news/Kind=2/newsId=38322.html Comfortable victory for Tadesse in C<U+00E1>ceres Half Marathon]. [[IAAF]]. Retrieved on 2009-10-16.</ref> He returned to the Great Manchester Run and again improved his best, recording 27:24, but this was not enough to beat Micah Kogo who won in a UK all-comers record time.<ref>Martin, David (2007-05-20). [http://www.iaaf.org/history/WXC/season=2007/eventCode=3651/news/kind=100/newsid=38752.html 27:21 victory by Kogo in Manchester]. [[IAAF]]. Retrieved on 2009-10-16.</ref> He competed at the [[Prefontaine Classic]] for the first time, and set a two miles best of 8:19.34, although he was some distance behind winner Craig Mottram.<ref>[http://www.iaaf.org/history/GP/season=2007/results/eventCode=3796/sex=M/discCode=2MLS/result.html#M2MLS 2007 Prefontaine Classic]. [[IAAF]] (2007-06-10). Retrieved on 2009-10-16.</ref>

The [[2007 All-Africa Games]] represented a double landmark victory for Tadese: he became the first Eritrean medallist in the competition's history, and won his first ever gold medal on the track, sealing victory in the [[Athletics at the 2007 All-Africa Games|10,000 m final]] with a [[List of All-Africa Games records in athletics|Games record]] time of 27:00.30.<ref>Powell, David (2007-07-19). [http://www.iaaf.org/news/Kind=2/newsId=39860.html In Algiers, another landmark for Tadesse - All Africa Games day 2]. [[IAAF]]. Retrieved on 2009-10-16.</ref> The following month he competed at the [[2007 World Championships in Athletics]], and he edged closer to a podium finish <U+2013> he led the [[2007 World Championships in Athletics <U+2013> Men's 10,000 metres|10,000 m race]] up to the 8&nbsp;km mark, setting a fast pace, but ultimately ended up in fourth position.<ref>[http://osaka2007.iaaf.org/news/kind=4/newsid=40725.html#event+report+mens+000m+final Event report: men's 10,000m Final]. [[IAAF]] (2007-08-27). Retrieved on 2009-10-16.</ref> Preparing for the road championships that year, he ran the 10-mile [[Dam tot Damloop]] race in September and won in 45:51 (the world's fastest that season), finishing some distance ahead of runners up [[Bernard Kipyego]] and [[James Rotich]].<ref>van Hemert, Wim (2007-09-24). [http://www.iaaf.org/history/WRU/season=2007/eventCode=3654/news/kind=100/newsid=41861.html World champion Tadesse makes Udine preparations with 'Dam tot Dam' loop win]. [[IAAF]]. Retrieved on 2009-10-16.</ref> Tadese emphasised his position as one of the world's most dominant half marathon runners with a second victory at the [[2007 IAAF World Road Running Championships]] in [[Udine]], Italy. Although he was close to world record pace at the 15&nbsp;km point, he slowed behind the leading pack of [[Makau Musyoki]], [[Evans Kiprop Cheruiyot]] and [[Deriba Merga]]. In the final kilometre, he burst away to take the lead and the gold medal, setting a national and championship record time of 58:59 in the process.<ref>Turner, Chris (2007-10-14). [http://www.iaaf.org/history/WRU/season=2007/eventCode=3654/news/kind=100/newsid=42080.html <U+2018>It felt like the whole of Eritrea was running with me<U+2019> - Tadese]. [[IAAF]]. Retrieved on 2009-10-16.</ref> Following these achievements, a medical team did a study of his [[running economy]] and found him to be one of the most efficient runners ever to be tested.<ref name=Wheel/><ref>[http://bjsm.bmj.com/cgi/content/extract/42/3/172 The key to top-level endurance running performance: a unique example]. [[British Journal of Sports Medicine]] (2007-11-27). Retrieved on 2009-10-19.</ref>

==World Half Marathon champion==
Bekele was keen to regain his cross country title from Tadese and the 2008 cross country season was a competitive one. At the [[Great Edinburgh International Cross Country]] race, Tadese was pipped by the Ethiopian at the line, finishing just one second behind.<ref>Landells, Steve (2008-01-12) [http://www.iaaf.org/WXC08/news/kind=100/newsid=42883.html Bekele strikes back, Burka defends - Edinburgh Cross Country report]. [[IAAF]]. Retrieved on 2009-10-16.</ref> The following month, Tadese beat [[Eliud Kipchoge]] to win the [[Cinque Mulini]] race in the build up to the [[2008 IAAF World Cross Country Championships]].<ref>Sampaulo, Diego (2008-02-03). [http://www.iaaf.org/WXC08/news/kind=100/newsid=43107.html World champion Tadese rules at the Cinque Mulini]. [[IAAF]]. Retrieved on 2009-10-16.</ref> On the day of the Championships race in [[Edinburgh]], [[Scotland]], Tadese took the lead early on and set a strong pace at the mid-race point. However, near the finish Bekele and Kenyan [[Leonard Komon]] surged ahead to leave Tadese as the bronze medallist.<ref>Powell, David (2008-03-30). [http://www.iaaf.org/WXC08/news/kind=108/newsid=44252.html Senior Men's Race Report - Edinburgh 2008]. [[IAAF]]. Retrieved on 2009-10-18.</ref>

A win at the [[World 10K Bangalore]], where he beat [[Moses Kipsiro]] in 27:51, was the highlight of a low-key build up to the [[2008 Beijing Olympics]].<ref>Krishnan, Ram. Murali (2008-05-18). [http://www.iaaf.org/WHM08/news/kind=100/newsid=44933.html Tadese the men<U+2019>s 10km victor, while Abeylegesse and Momanyi share women<U+2019>s spoils in Bangalore]. [[IAAF]]. Retrieved on 2009-10-18.</ref> In August, Tadese was among some forty runners competing for the medals [[Athletics at the 2008 Summer Olympics <U+2013> Men's 10,000 metres|10,000 metres Olympic final]]. Tadese's brother, [[Kidane Tadese|Kidane]], was also competing and he led for most of first half of what was a quick race. Zersenay Tadese had the lead at the 7<U+2013>8&nbsp;km mark but Bekele and Sihine sprinted into first and second. Although Tadese's time almost equalled the [[List of Olympic records in athletics|Olympic record]] for the event, he also ended up one second behind Kenyans [[Moses Masai]] and Kogo, taking fifth place overall.<ref>Ramsak, Bob (2008-08-17). [http://www.iaaf.org/OLY08/news/kind=108/newsid=46800.html Men's 10,000m FINAL]. [[IAAF]]. Retrieved on 2009-10-19.</ref> After the Olympics, Tadese returned to Eritrea and trained for one month to prepare for the [[2008 IAAF World Half Marathon Championships|2008 World Half Marathon Championships]] in [[Rio de Janeiro]].<ref>Davies, Nick & Turner, Chris (2008-10-11). [http://www.iaaf.org/WHM08/news/kind=100/newsid=47997.html Kiplagat, Tadese and Dos Santos reflect on Beijing and look forward World Half Marathon, Rio 2008]. [[IAAF]]. Retrieved on 2009-10-19.</ref> He won his third consecutive title over the half marathon distance with ease, taking the lead early on and beating the second-placed Patrick Makau Musyoki by almost two minutes.<ref>Turner, Chris (2008-10-12). [http://www.iaaf.org/WHM08/news/kind=100/newsid=48010.html Emphatic third triumph; Tadese goes solo from 5km - Men's Race Report, Rio 2008]. [[IAAF]]. Retrieved on 2009-10-19.</ref> His success caused much celebration in his home country, so much so that the [[President of Eritrea]] greeted him at the airport upon his return. With a strong history in the half marathon, Tadese announced he would try the full marathon distance the following season.<ref>Turner, Chris (2008-10-12). [http://www.iaaf.org/WHM08/news/kind=100/newsid=48021.html Tadese <U+2013> confident in victory and his sporting plans at least <U+2013> Rio 2008]. [[IAAF]]. Retrieved on 2009-10-19.</ref>

Tadese took third place at the [[2009 IAAF World Cross Country Championships]] in a closely contested race, finishing just behind a resurgent [[Gebre-egziabher Gebremariam]] and Ugandan runner Moses Kipsiro.<ref>Powell, David (2009-03-28). [http://www.iaaf.org/WXC09/news/newsid=49967.html Senior Men<U+2019>s Race Report <U+2013> Amman 2009]. [[IAAF]]. Retrieved on 2009-10-19.</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/athletics/7968791.stm Kiplagat powers to world triumph]. [[BBC Sport]] (2009-03-28). Retrieved on 2009-03-30.</ref> He competed in his first ever full-length [[marathon]] in April, signing up for the [[London Marathon]]. His first appearance over the distance was much anticipated following his cross country and track success, but he could not finish the race, pulling out around the 35&nbsp;km mark.<ref>[[Steve Cram|Cram, Steve]] (2009-04-21). [http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/blog/2009/apr/21/london-marathon-zersenay-tadese-steve-cram Zersenay Tadese can light up this year's London Marathon]. ''[[The Guardian]]''. Retrieved on 2009-10-12.</ref><ref>Wilson, Steve (2009-04-26). [http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/athletics/london-marathon/5224481/2009-London-Marathon-Olympic-champion-Sammy-Wanjiru-wins-in-new-course-record.html 2009 London Marathon: Olympic champion Sammy Wanjiru wins in new course record]. ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''. Retrieved on 2009-10-12.</ref>

He rebounded, however, taking silver in the [[2009 World Championships in Athletics <U+2013> Men's 10,000 metres|10,000 metres]] at the [[2009 World Championships in Athletics]], finishing behind [[Kenenisa Bekele]]. Tadese had led for a large part of the race, setting a fast pace, but he was beaten to the gold by Bekele's sprint finish. Following this, he won his third [[2009 IAAF World Half Marathon Championships|World Half Marathon]] title, setting a [[IAAF World Half Marathon Championships|Championship record]] of 59:35 and also winning a silver medal with Eritrea in the team competition.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/athletics/8301315.stm Tadese seals half marathon treble ]. [[BBC Sport]] (2009-10-11). Retrieved on 2009-10-11.</ref> The gold medal over the half marathon distance made him the second runner ever to win a World Championship medal in cross country, track and road racing all in the same year, a feat achieved previously by only [[Paul Tergat]].<ref name=Surfaces/>

==Personal life==
A quietly spoken athlete,<ref name=Wheel/> he frequently states that his victories are a tribute to his country.<ref name=FirstWC/><ref name=Focus/> Eritrea is one of [[Africa]]'s newest and less populous countries, and Tadese's achievements on the world athletics stage have made him one of the country's most identifiable sportsmen. He is a popular public figure in his home country; 2500 guests attended his wedding to Merhawit Solomon, which was broadcast live on Eritrean television.<ref name=Surfaces/><ref name=Focus/> His brother, [[Kidane Tadese]], is also a professional distance runner who has competed at the World Cross Country Championships and the 2008 Summer Olympics.<ref>[http://www.iaaf.org/athletes/biographies/letter=T/country=ERI/athcode=205947/index.html Biography Tadese Kidane]. [[IAAF]]. Retrieved on 2009-10-22.</ref>

